Now I need to understand the issue better. From the issue description:

1. A single-line lambda like `{ size -> icon?.getBitmap(size)?.await() }` is being incorrectly wrapped
2. When wrapped, it produces odd indentation where the parameter line is indented more than the body

Looking at the `rearrangeArrow` function (lines 495-533), this is where the logic for handling arrows in lambdas is. The issue mentions that this is related to #2106 and #2101, where the parameter list is being incorrectly wrapped when it should remain on a single line.

Let me look at the key part:

```kotlin
private fun rearrangeArrow(
    node: ASTNode,
    autoCorrect: Boolean,
    emit: (offset: Int, errorMessage: String, canBeAutoCorrected: Boolean) -> Unit,
) {
    val p = node.treeParent
    if (
        // check
        // `{ p -> ... }`
        // and
        // `when { m -> ... }`
        // only
        p.elementType.let { it != FUNCTION_LITERAL && it != WHEN_ENTRY } ||
        // ... and only if expression after -> spans multiple lines
        !p.textContains('\n') ||
        // permit
        // when {
        //     m -> 0 + d({
        //     })
        // }
        (p.elementType == WHEN_ENTRY && mustBeFollowedByNewline(node)) ||
        // permit
        // when (this) {
        //     in 0x1F600..0x1F64F, // Emoticons
        //     0x200D // Zero-width Joiner
        //     -> true
        // }
        (p.elementType == WHEN_ENTRY && node.prevLeaf()?.textContains('\n') == true)
    ) {
        return
    }
    if (!node.nextCodeLeaf()?.prevLeaf().isWhiteSpaceWithNewline()) {
        requireNewlineAfterLeaf(node, autoCorrect, emit)
    }
    val r = node.nextSibling { it.elementType == RBRACE } ?: return
    if (!r.prevLeaf().isWhiteSpaceWithNewline()) {
        requireNewlineBeforeLeaf(r, autoCorrect, emit, node.indent())
    }
}
```

I see the function is checking various conditions to determine when to enforce newline formatting. The code checks the parent element type, whether the expression spans multiple lines, and ensures proper newline placement before and after the arrow. It seems designed to handle different lambda and when-entry scenarios while maintaining consistent code formatting.

The current implementation has a specific limitation with lambda parameter detection. The existing check only recognizes parameters when they're in a formal VALUE_PARAMETER_LIST, which misses lambda parameter scenarios where parameters are just identifiers followed by an arrow. This means the formatting logic won't correctly handle certain lambda parameter styles.

I'll need to investigate how to modify the detection mechanism to recognize these alternative lambda parameter representations more comprehensively.

